{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491638"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:56:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:56:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1005"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1005"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.12,0.03,0.66,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1005"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50668"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1005"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1005"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35903"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"8842"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5490"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5739"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50668"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with pain in his left eye. Four hours earlier he had been inadvertently hit in the eye whilst playing squash. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he has decreased visual acuity in the left eye, with diplopia on upward and downward gaze. There is no proptosis. Intraocular pressures are normal in both eyes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Corneal laceration","Retrobulbar haemorrhage","Lateral subconjunctival haemorrhage","Fracture of the orbital floor","Dislocation of the lens"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has suffered from blunt trauma to the left eye. Complications of blunt orbital trauma include orbital floor fracture, hyphaema, traumatic cataract, iridodialysis, retinal detachment, globe rupture, and retrobulbar haemorrhage amongst others.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFracture of the orbital floor\u003C/strong\u003E is suggested by the diplopia on vertical gaze. The inferior rectus muscle can become trapped in orbital floor fractures. The decreased visual acuity may be secondary to traumatic optic neuropathy. If enophthalmos (posterior displacement of the eye) is noted, this suggests significant prolapse of orbital contents (fat and sometimes the inferior rectus muscle belly).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorneal laceration\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely with blunt trauma than with penetrating trauma. Additionally, it does not explain the diplopia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetrobulbar haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E is a potential complication of blunt trauma. It will however present with unilateral proptosis on the affected side. Extraocular muscle movements will be generally restricted, as opposed to diplopia just on vertical gaze.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral subconjunctival haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Elens dislocation\u003C/strong\u003E may be seen with blunt trauma. However, these injuries will not cause isolated extraocular muscle restriction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Blunt orbital trauma may cause orbital floor fractures.","Orbital floor fractures can cause entrapment of the inferior rectus muscle leading to diplopia on vertical gaze."],"references":["Heath-Jeffrey RC. Dobes J, Chen FK. , Aust J Gen Pract 2022; 51:476-82"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35903"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1005"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35903"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-15T20:51:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-15T20:52:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1005"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50668"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1193"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Eye pain","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-07-31T01:47:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:43:27+10:30"},"relations